% Ghostscript's own examples assume a few operators that Ghostscript
% provides -- as public extensions (min, max) or internal operators
% (.min, .max) -- but the PostScript Language Reference Manual does not
% define. Supplying them here, to both the reference and xpost so the
% comparison stays fair, lets the pristine examples run without editing
% them. These are not xpost operators and their absence is not a defect.
/min where { pop } { /min { 2 copy gt { exch } if pop } bind def } ifelse
/max where { pop } { /max { 2 copy lt { exch } if pop } bind def } ifelse
/.min where { pop } { /.min /min load def } ifelse
/.max where { pop } { /.max /max load def } ifelse
